                        "description": "<p><strong>Selection Phase </strong></p><p>Glass slides (15.25 cm^2) were placed as substrate in 20 L glass tanks and unfiltered river water from the Parthe river, a local stream (sampling point: 51\u00b022'18.5'N 12\u00b025'07.7'E) served as inoculum for biofilm growth. The glass slide holder had varying spatial position (up, mid and low), which were approximately 10, 13 and 16 cm below water surface. Biofilms were grown for 5 wk, and half of the glass tanks were contaminated with 4 \u00b5g/L <strong>diuron</strong>, starting from the second week of cultivation. Water was stirred permanently and exchanged weekly to guarantee sufficient supply of nutrients and a near-natural inoculum of species. The exposure concentration of <strong>diuron</strong> was renewed after each water exchange and monitored before and after <strong>diuron</strong> addition on a QTRAP 6500 LC-MS/MS System. Oxygen saturation, pH and temperature were monitored at each water exchange. Water temperature was maintained at 22\u00b11 \u00b0C and the light cycle was set to 14/10 h light/dark cycle. The photon yield of the LED plant lamps (C-series, Valoya, Helsinki, Finland) above the water surface was approximately 150 \u00b5mol photons m^2/s.</p><p><br></p><p><strong>Detection Phase </strong></p><p>After the selection phase the slides were randomly sampled from the different tanks at varying spatial position (up, mid and low) to avoid a spatial bias in the microbial community. The slides were exposed for a second time in 500 mL petri dishes and each concentration was duplicated, while controls were triplicated. The <strong>diuron</strong> exposure solution was equilibrated for 30 min prior to biofilm addition and then an aliquot for exposure monitoring was taken. Light and temperature parameters of the second exposure were kept consistent with the settings of the selection phase using a phytotron (MultitronPro, IFORS, Einsbach, Germany). Petri dishes were slightly agitated at 30 rpm and illuminated by LEDs. After 1 h of exposure the slides were sampled by transferring them 50 mL falcon tubes. The tubes were immediately quenched in liquid nitrogen and stored until extraction at -80 \u00b0C.</p>",
