                    {
                        "comments": [],
                        "name": "Extraction",
                        "protocolType": {
                            "comments": [],
                            "annotationValue": "Extraction",
                            "termSource": null,
                            "termAccession": ""
                        },
                        "description": "<p>First, 20 mg of a freeze dried sample was transferred into a FastPrep\u00ae tube. Then 150 mg of glass beads (5 mm) and 1.2 mL of a solvent mixture containing methanol, chloroform and water (10:5:4, v/v/v) and ribitol as internal standard (10 mg/L) was added to each sample. Cells were disrupted using a FastPrep\u00ae-24 (MP Biomedicals, USA) for 35 s in 3 cycles, while the samples were cooled down for 2 min after each run. Cell debris were centrifuged (6 min, 6 \u00b0C, 20000 x g, rotor 12148) and 1 mL of the supernatant, 0.8 mL milli-Q water and 1.6 mL chloroform were transferred into a 10 mL glass tube. The hydrophilic and lipophilic metabolites were separated by vortexing and a subsequent centrifugation step (10 min, 5 \u00b0C, 4000 x g, rotor). A total of 1 mL of the upper hydrophilic methanol/water (polar) phase was transferred into a 3 mL reaction glass vial and dried at 40 \u00b0C and gentle nitrogen circulation. The dried sample was incubated with 200 \u00b5L MOXTM reagent (2% methoxyamine x HCl in pyridine) for 2 h at 80 \u00b0C. The methoxaminated samples were dried the same way as before, 100 \u00b5L of MSTFA reagent was added and they were incubated at 90 \u00b0C for 20 min. Process blanks were included in the metabolite extraction and derivatization step to account and subtract the background contamination. After derivatization a pool sample (QC sample) from all individual samples was created by pooling 10 \u00b5L of each sample. Then the samples were subjected to a gas chromatograph coupled to a time-of-flight mass spectrometer (GC-TOFMS).&nbsp;</p>",
