                    {
                        "comments": [],
                        "name": "Data transformation",
                        "protocolType": {
                            "comments": [],
                            "annotationValue": "Data transformation",
                            "termSource": null,
                            "termAccession": ""
                        },
                        "description": "<p>The raw data was aligned using the free software \u2018<strong>MS-DIAL</strong>\u2019 version 4.24. The alignment table was corrected, filtered, normalized, aggregated, transformed and visualized. First the alignment was quality checked for peaks that were divided into different alignment ID\u2019s. Those peaks were merged if the EI spectrum similarity was above 80%, the retention time gap was below 8 s and the conflict between the aligned metabolites was below 5%. In total 57 of the 1354 aligned peaks were merged with their corresponding counterpart to correct for peak splitting in the alignment routine. The dataset was filtered for artifacts, which were introduced by the <strong>MS-DIAL</strong> alignment (automatically interpolated peak areas) and sporadically occurring peaks. To this end data were filtered for consistency by requiring a peak to occur at a minimum of 30% in the replicates of 3 subsequent treatments. The filtering revealed 601 sporadic peaks which were removed. In a last filtering step the blank contamination was removed by setting a 5-fold threshold, which the mean peak area must exceed compared to the blank mean. The blank filtering step further reduced the dataset to a final selection of 190 metabolites, which were normalized to the internal standard ribitol. Then, the replicates of each exposure treatment were aggregated to a mean value, since they covered the different slide positions (up, mid and low) during cultivation. Finally, the aggregated data was mean centered and auto-scaled for the principal component analysis.</p>",
